# 🔌 Application Bootstrapping & Graceful Disconnection Hooks

TODO:
[√] Import module entry boundary to invoke background tracking instances
[ ] Trap operating system termination loops to safe-stop execution queues

[js] Application Main Core Root Server:
File Location: `src/index.ts`
```typescript
import express from "express";
import dotenv from "dotenv";

dotenv.config();
const app = express();

app.use(express.json());

// 🚀 Bootstrap Email Domain Subsystem (Spawns worker background instance automatically)
import { emailWorker } from "./modules/email/index.js";

// Standard termination tracking processor function hook
const executeGracefulShutdown = async (signal: string) => {
  console.log(`\n🚨 [${signal}] Signal received. Closing background thread execution pools safely...`);
  
  // Refuses processing any fresh jobs from Redis, but lets current running tasks complete safely
  await emailWorker.close();
  
  console.log("🔒 Worker processing threads terminated. Exiting system engine smoothly.");
  process.exit(0);
};

// Intercept OS system event signals to completely bypass data-loss bugs on hot deploys
process.on("SIGINT", () => executeGracefulShutdown("SIGINT"));
process.on("SIGTERM", () => executeGracefulShutdown("SIGTERM"));

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("⚡ Main enterprise backend system operational at network socket: 3000");
});
```

---

# ❌ Critical Debug Ledger (Common Mistakes)

[x] Mistake: Issuing hard process exit loops (`process.exit(1)`) while the background worker is in the middle of executing a 1.5-second network nodemailer API transport stream. The task ends up permanently hanging inside the active Redis data cluster state.
[√] Fix: Invoke the asynchronous `await worker.close()` lifecycle promise hook engine inside system OS `SIGTERM` / `SIGINT` trapping routines before shutting down the container wrapper process.





